
Q)What is Kubernetes, and what problems does it solve?
Kubernetes is an open-source container orchestration platform used to automate the deployment, scaling, management, and monitoring of containerized applications.

    It was originally developed by Google and is now maintained by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation.
    
    Kubernetes helps manage containers across multiple servers (nodes) in a cluster environment.

Kubernetes solves several challenges in managing containerized applications:
    Automates container deployment and management
    Provides auto scaling based on traffic/load
    Restarts failed containers automatically (self-healing)
    Ensures high availability of applications
    Handles load balancing and service discovery
    Supports rolling updates and easy rollbacks
    Efficiently manages CPU, memory, and storage resources
    Simplifies management of large-scale microservices applications
    Provides portability across cloud and on-premises environments
 
    
Q) What are the main components of Kubernetes architecture, and how do they work together?

1. Control Plane (Master Node)
    Manages and controls the cluster.
        Main components:
            API Server → Entry point for all Kubernetes operations
            etcd → Stores cluster data and configuration
            Scheduler → Assigns Pods to nodes
            Controller Manager → Maintains desired cluster state

2. Worker Node
    Runs the application workloads (Pods).
        Main components:
            kubelet → Communicates with Control Plane and manages Pods
            kube-proxy → Handles networking and traffic routing
            Container Runtime → Runs containers (e.g., containerd)

Simple Flow
User → API Server → Scheduler selects node → kubelet creates Pod → container runtime runs container.


Q) What is the difference between the Control Plane and Worker Nodes? (optional)

In Simple Words
Control Plane = Brain of Kubernetes
Worker Node = Machine that runs applications (Pods)


Q) What is the role of the API Server, Scheduler, Controller Manager, and etcd in Kubernetes?

API Server → Entry point of the cluster. It receives all requests from users, kubectl, and other components and communicates with the cluster.
Scheduler → Decides on which Worker Node a Pod should run based on resources, policies, and constraints.
Controller Manager → Continuously monitors the cluster and ensures the desired state is maintained (e.g., recreates failed Pods).
etcd → Distributed key-value store that stores all cluster data and configuration information. It acts as the cluster database.


Q) What is kubelet, kube-proxy, and Container Runtime?

kubelet → Agent running on each Worker Node. It communicates with the Control Plane and ensures Pods are running as expected.
kube-proxy → Handles networking on Worker Nodes. It manages traffic routing and load balancing between Pods and Services.
Container Runtime → Software responsible for running containers on a node. Examples include containerd and CRI-O.

What happens internally when you run kubectl apply?

kubectl sends the YAML/manifest request to the API Server.
The API Server validates the configuration.
The desired state is stored in etcd.
The Scheduler selects a suitable Worker Node for the Pod.
The kubelet on that node receives instructions from the API Server.
The Container Runtime pulls the container image and starts the containers.
kube-proxy configures networking and service communication.
The Pod becomes running, and Kubernetes continuously monitors it to maintain the desired state.



